This page is a supplementary teaching scaffold for AST semantics.

## Core concept

The AST stage turns parsed declaration shapes and expressions into checked semantic meaning.

## Beanstalk boundary

AST owns:

- module-local declaration resolution
- local type-environment construction
- executable body parsing and type checking
- contextual coercion at explicit receiving sites
- constant and template folding
- generic call inference and request emission
- trait, conformance and cast evidence
- public-surface validation
- entry metadata folding
- TIR from parser emission through finalisation

AST consumes bound visibility and local declaration order. It does not rediscover imports or provider declarations.

## Rewrite focus

Explain the difference between syntax trees and typed semantic trees, why environment construction precedes body checking and why compile-time evaluation must agree with runtime semantics.

Canonical details live in `docs/compiler-design-overview.md`.
